              h2 The Continuous Learning Dilemma - It's Real!
              p
                | Last week I described ‚ÄúThe Continuous Learning Dilemma‚Äù that I believe all of us as IT people
                | and organisations are facing. I don‚Äôt believe it‚Äôs a small challenge, neither do I believe it‚Äôs
                | going away any time soon. It‚Äôs a challenge we all must face and overcome if we are to be
                | successful as individuals, teams and organisations.

              p
                | Some people would say it‚Äôs not so much a challenge as an opportunity!
                | If IT was ‚Äúeasy‚Äù anybody could do it. In reality it's an infinite game i.e. we never really win,
                | we just aim to stay playing!
              
              p
                | At Capgemini we welcome this challenge as an opportunity to demonstrate our breadth of knowledge
                | and technical dexterity.

              h3 Out Of My Comfort Zone

              p
                | In my role as Capabilities Lead within the Digital Delivery Group (DDG) a couple of things take
                | me out of my comfort zone. One is building my people network, the other is the battle for hearts
                | and minds. These aren‚Äôt strengths for me but I‚Äôm happy to learn as well as ride on the coat-tails
                | of others, especially when they offer to extend my network into the wider Capgemini (200K+
                | people) and beyond.

              h3 Collaboration Required

              p
                | None of the challenges we take on at Capgemini can ever be considered small enough for just one
                | person to deal with and so team effort and collaboration with others is a must. The challenge of
                | the continuous learning dilemma is no different ‚Äì in fact it‚Äôs going to take the brains of the
                | whole IT industry (and then some) to solve this one! Fortunately, collaborative working is a
                | means of putting your own limitations behind you and playing to your strengths and those of others.

              h3 Choosing An Approach

              p
                img#mugshot.img-thumbnail.img-responsive(src='../images/plates-spinning.jpg', alt='Spinning Plates', title='Spinning Plates')
                | The approach to this challenge must be agile (in order to get feedback fast, learn and adapt)
                | and multi-threaded because success will be through multiple people and ideas running in parallel.
                | The approach also has to generate metrics that will help us. It will be like ‚Äúspinning plates‚Äù.
                | Effort will be needed to keep plates spinning and to spin up new ones. Some plates will
                | inevitably get broken along the way ‚Äì maybe we won‚Äôt count those, just learn from them.

              p
                | I know that I can‚Äôt expect to do this role well without working with and through a network of
                | people and that I also need to ‚Äútake people with me‚Äù along the way. (This means finding people
                | willing to keep plates spinning for me.)

              p
                | My background thread is ‚ÄúContinuous Research‚Äù where I periodically research (usually daily for
                | a few minutes making notes of keywords and useful links) in order to learn from the best around
                | the world. Thankyou Internet.

              h3 The Battle For Hearts and Minds

              p
                | Winning hearts and minds is just plain hard to me. The necessity and benefits of making learning
                | part of the day job seem obvious to me and I can‚Äôt always understand why others don‚Äôt see that.

              p
                | Selling is clearly a skill in it‚Äôs own right. I swear that if there were no people involved,
                | doing IT would be a doddle!

              p
                | It took me a while to learn and accept that people are motivated by different priorities and so
                | the same ‚Äúsales pitch‚Äù isn‚Äôt appropriate for all customers. For managers it is often about
                | hitting budgets and deadlines ahead of anything else to please our customers (and our accountants)
                | which doesn‚Äôt always align with the company mantra ‚ÄúPeople matter, results count‚Äù. Fortunately not
                | everyone is short-sighted. (I‚Äôm literally long-sighted. üòä)

