              h2 The Continuous Learning Spectrum - Theory or Reality?

              p
                | If the above spectrum is true, the questions that immediately arise include what percentage of people
                | currently fit into each category and how can we move the sliders to shift people between categories to
                | achieve the optimal numbers we desire? Categorisation is only a theory until you have a means of
                | applying it to generate metrics. (We‚Äôll look deeper into this in a future post.)

              h3 1)	The Trail Blazers

              p
                | Some people (Google call them ‚Äúlearning animals‚Äù) are already there with continuous learning
                | and they‚Äôre so busy loving learning new stuff in new ways and applying it in their work that
                | they don‚Äôt even look backwards to see the others they‚Äôve left behind! I need to throw a rope
                | around these guys and work out how to get them dragging others with them.

              p
                | These people are often less in number and in high demand. They are candidates for coaching,
                | knowledge sharing and involvement in community activities if they are not already doing so.
                | These are some of the people we‚Äôd really like to clone. (Ultimately we‚Äôd like everyone in
                | this category ‚Äì job done.)

              h3 2)	The Well-Intentioned Majority

              p
                | Most people relate reasonably well to the necessity to learn new skills and are
                | well-intentioned about learning. However, many suffer from sub-optimal time management skills
                | coupled with a strong desire (and project pressure) to delight the customer which both
                | inevitably impact commitment to learning. Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I‚Äôm not saying that learning is
                | more important than delighting customers but what I am saying is that learning is essential
                | to delighting customers and so getting the balance right in terms of how we manage our time
                | is extremely important.

              p
                | These guys need direction as well as help managing their time and support and encouragement
                | from managers for learning.

              h3 3)	The Partially Convinced

              p
                | Here the battle for hearts and minds is still being fought or yet to be fought. The ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs
                | in it for me?‚Äù question has not been suitably answered. Here the learning approach is a
                | little ‚Äúad hoc‚Äù and more a response to pressure. New ways of learning attract minimal levels
                | of interest unless provoked. Another form of motivation is required here.

              h3 4)	The Not Convinced

              p
                | Here the battle for hearts and minds has been lost. The value-proposition answer to the
                | ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs in it for me?‚Äù question did not align at all with the motivations / priorities of
                | these people. Continuous learning is perceived to be an anti-pattern that may hinder
                | delivering on time and to budget and is simply not necessary for personal success right
                | now. Only leadership direction can change this position.

              h3 5) The Minimalist Minority

              p
                | Some will say that people who don‚Äôt want to learn new things or who resist change
                | shouldn‚Äôt be working in the IT industry where change is constant. That‚Äôs not a helpful
                | viewpoint when such people are talented and performing significant roles that they enjoy
                | but which dominate their time ‚Äì including their learning time. They may also be generating
                | significant revenue for the business in doing so. (Don‚Äôt you just love this dilemma?!)

              p
                | There is also a minority who resist change or are apathetic. Management intervention is
                | required here. (Such people leave me wondering if even dynamite would make a difference!
                | üòä However, we are not planning on leaving anyone behind.)

              h2 Building People

              p
                | In any large organisation you can sometimes feel like a small wheel with a number in a big
                | machine where managing your career is your problem. However, my role as DDG Capabilities
                | Lead is to ‚Äúbuild people‚Äù which is a Lean Thinking concept that I greatly admire and strive
                | to achieve each day. Another Lean Thinking concept is ‚Äúchallenging the status quo‚Äù and I
                | seek to do that each day too.

              h3 "T-Shaped" People

              p
                | At Capgemini we like people to be ‚ÄúT-shaped‚Äù in terms of their knowledge and skills i.e.
                | to have both breadth and depth: breadth in many things and depth in a few. We encourage
                | people to have their own areas of interest and to know what they want to be ‚Äúfamous‚Äù for.

              h3 "Pi-Shaped" People

              p
                | I recently saw a description of "Pi-shaped (&pi;)" people who had "two deep skills" as opposed
                | to the "one very deep skill" of "T-shaped" people. This seems unrealistic to me as it's so rare
                | for people to have or need just one or two deep skills when most skills have many closely 
                | related (adjacent) skills so there is rarely a single learning curve.
                | I'm also not really able to grasp the difference between "deep" and "very deep" skills. 

